    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from jupyterthemes import jtplot\n",

  {

   "id": "423eefb3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8cc8108e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The data object contains the time-bins and observed counts in the individual energy channels. It can also be used to rebin the data in new, longer, time bins."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "4796b756",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-31T11:18:03.387192Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-31T11:18:03.386719Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-31T11:18:04.053335Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-31T11:18:04.052527Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from gbmbkgpy.data.gbm_data import GBMData\n",
    "# get daily GBM data\n",
    "gbmdata = GBMData(name=\"gbmn0\", \n",
    "                date=\"200510\", \n",
    "                data_type=\"ctime\", \n",
    "                detector=\"n6\", \n",
    "                echans=[\"1\",\"2\",\"3-5\"])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Rebin the data to 20 second bins\n",
    "gbmdata.rebin_data(min_bin_width=20)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "04e53db9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "410f1322",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Geometry"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "05bb59bb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The data object contains the information how to transform a position in icrs coords (ra and dec) to the satellite coordinate system (az and el) (and the opposite way) for any given time. It also needs a method that returns if a given position in icrs coordinates is occulted by the earth at a given time."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "985f165e",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-31T11:18:04.228041Z",

     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-31T11:18:06.423865Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-31T11:18:06.423100Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from gbmbkgpy.geometry.gbm_geometry import GBMGeometryPosHist\n",
    "\n",
    "# init geometry object for Fermi/GBM at the given date\n",
    "geom = GBMGeometryPosHist(date=\"200510\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ca9a223a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Transform icrs to satellite frame"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "4daa0a26",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-31T11:18:06.427890Z",

    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "ICRS (50, 0) -> Satellite (356.87197857243024, 21.23785882753735)\n",
      "ICRS (100, 0) -> Satellite (44.47341520675653, 2.3454518134180518)\n",
      "ICRS (150, 0) -> Satellite (90.85021846482132, -18.03688027053613)\n",

   "source": [
    "time = round(gbmdata.mean_time[100])\n",
    "ra = [50, 100, 150, 200, 250]\n",
    "dec = [0, 0, 0, 0, 0]\n",
    "az, el = geom.icrs_to_satellite(time, ra, dec)\n",
    "for (a, e, r, d) in zip(az, el, ra, dec):\n",
    "    print(f\"ICRS ({r}, {d}) -> Satellite ({a}, {e})\")"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0a55f6f8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Check if some points are occulted by the earth at a certain time"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "de6dd64a",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-31T11:18:06.437226Z",

     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-31T11:18:06.441848Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "ICRS (50, 0) is not occulted by earth at time 610763637 s\n",
      "ICRS (100, 0) is not occulted by earth at time 610763637 s\n",
      "ICRS (150, 0) is not occulted by earth at time 610763637 s\n",
      "ICRS (200, 0) is occulted by earth at time 610763637 s\n",
      "ICRS (250, 0) is occulted by earth at time 610763637 s\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "time = round(gbmdata.mean_time[100])\n",
    "ra = [50, 100, 150, 200, 250]\n",
    "dec = [0, 0, 0, 0, 0]\n",
    "occ = geom.is_occulted(time, ra, dec)\n",
    "for (o, r, d) in zip(occ, ra, dec):\n",
    "    if o:\n",
    "        print(f\"ICRS ({r}, {d}) is occulted by earth at time {time} s\")\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        print(f\"ICRS ({r}, {d}) is not occulted by earth at time {time} s\")"
   ]
  },

   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

    "drm_gen = GBMResponseGenerator(geometry=geom, det=\"n6\", Ebins_in_edge=np.geomspace(10,2000, 101), data=gbmdata)"

    "from gbmbkgpy.response.src_response import EarthResponse, CGBResponse, GalacticCenterResponse\n",
    "\n",
    "# Time where to calculate the effective responses - linear interpolation in between\n",
    "interp_time = np.linspace(gbmdata.time_bins[0,0], gbmdata.time_bins[-1,-1], 800)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Galactic Center\n",
    "gc_rsp = GalacticCenterResponse(geometry=geom, interp_times=interp_time, resp_prec=rsp_pre)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Earth Albedo\n",
    "earth_rsp = EarthResponse(geometry=geom, interp_times=interp_time, resp_prec=rsp_pre)\n",
    "\n",
    "# CGB\n",
    "cgb_rsp = CGBResponse(geometry=geom, interp_times=interp_time, resp_prec=rsp_pre)"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# Modelling"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "52f71b9d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here we first construct the different sources contributing to the background. The source can be split in two classes: PhotonSources that we can forward fold through the response (very good!) and particle sources that we can not forward fold due to the lack of a charged particle response or similar (not very good). The particle sources we therefore have to model directly in count space."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "89b6be41",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's start with the photon sources. We have to different kind of photon sources: PhotonSourceFixed and PhotonSourceFree. The difference is only important if we want to fit the background, because for PhotonSourceFixed sources only the normalization is free but for PhotonSourceFree also the spectral parameters are free. We stick with PhotonSourceFixed for the moment, because the fitting is not working at the moment.\n",
    "\n",
    "We use astromodels as the spectral modeling framework."
   ]
  },

    "from gbmbkgpy.modeling.source import PhotonSourceFixed\n",
    "from astromodels import Powerlaw\n",
    "from gbmbkgpy.modeling.new_astromodels import SBPL\n",
    "\n",
    "from astromodels.utils.configuration import astromodels_config\n",
    "astromodels_config.modeling.ignore_parameter_bounds = True\n",
    "\n",
    "# A point source\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define spectrum\n",
    "pl_crab = Powerlaw()\n",
    "pl_crab.K.value = 9.7\n",
    "pl_crab.index.value = -2.1\n",
    "\n",
    "# define source\n",
    "crab = PhotonSourceFixed(\"Crab\", pl_crab, crab_rsp)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# extended source\n",
    "\n",
    "#CGB\n",
    "# values taken from Ajello et al. 2008\n",
    "cgb_spec = SBPL()\n",
    "cgb_spec.K.value = 0.11\n",
    "cgb_spec.alpha.value = 1.32\n",
    "cgb_spec.beta.value = 2.88\n",
    "cgb_spec.xb.value = 30.0\n",
    "\n",
    "# define source\n",
    "cgb = PhotonSourceFixed(\"CGB\", cgb_spec, cgb_rsp)"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7833e8af",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next the particle sources. For the cosmic rays we use a cosmic ray tracer from the geometry object (McIlwain L-parameter at the satellite position) and the SAAs are modelled as exponetial decay. These source are modelled directly in count data space and we have no information how to connect the individual energy channels. Therefore we model it independent in every energy channel with the use of the AstromodelFunctionVector wrapper, that just copies the base_function for every energy channel."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "b2135688",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-10-31T11:19:19.408955Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-10-31T11:19:19.408510Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-10-31T11:19:19.416962Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-10-31T11:19:19.416360Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from gbmbkgpy.modeling.functions import AstromodelFunctionVector\n",
    "from gbmbkgpy.modeling.source import SAASource, NormOnlySource\n",
    "\n",
    "from astromodels import Exponential_cutoff, Constant\n",
    "\n",
    "# SAA\n",
    "exp_decay = Exponential_cutoff()\n",
    "exp_decay.K.value = 1000\n",
    "exp_decay.xc.value = 1000\n",
    "afv_saa = AstromodelFunctionVector(gbmdata.num_echan, base_function=exp_decay)\n",
    "\n",
    "# define the time when the satellite leaves the SAA\n",
    "exit_time_saa = gbmdata.mean_time[100]\n",
    "\n",
    "saa = SAASource(\"SAA\", exit_time_saa, afv_saa)\n",
    "\n",
    "# CR\n",
    "c = Constant()\n",
    "c.k.value = 100\n",
    "afv_cr = AstromodelFunctionVector(gbmdata.num_echan, base_function=c)\n",
    "\n",
    "cr = NormOnlySource(\"CR\", geom.cr_tracer, afv_cr)"
   ]
  },

    "Now we can create the model object that connects the sources with the data. This can be used to plot the total model against the data or also calculate the log_like of the current model configuration."

    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from gbmbkgpy.modeling.model import ModelDet\n",
    "\n",
    "model = ModelDet(gbmdata)\n",
    "\n",
    "model.add_source(cgb)\n",
    "model.add_source(crab)\n",
    "\n",
    "model.add_source(saa)\n",
    "model.add_source(cr)"
   ]
